<!-- PAGE 21-22: DFD -->
<div class="page">
  <div class="chapter-header">CHAPTER 5: DATA FLOW DIAGRAM</div>
  <p>A Data Flow Diagram (DFD) is a graphical representation of the flow of data through an information system. DFDs were developed by Larry Constantine as a method of expressing system requirements in a graphical form. They show how data moves through a system, what processes transform that data, and where data is stored.</p>
  <h4>DFD Symbols Used:</h4>
  <table>
    <tr><th>Symbol</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Rectangle</td><td>External Entity (data source or destination)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Rounded Rectangle / Circle</td><td>Process (transforms data)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Open Rectangle</td><td>Data Store (stored data)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Arrow</td><td>Data Flow (movement of data)</td></tr>
  </table>
  <h3>5.1: LEVEL 0 DFD (Context Level Diagram)</h3>
  <div class="dfd-box">
    <table style="border:none; width:100%;">
      <tr>
        <td style="border:none; text-align:center; width:25%;">
          <div style="border:2px solid #000; padding:10px; margin:5px;">STUDENT</div>
        </td>
        <td style="border:none; text-align:center; width:50%;">
          <div style="font-size:10pt;">-- Registration, Chat, AI Query --&gt;</div>
          <div style="border:3px solid #c0392b; padding:15px; margin:10px; background:#fff0f0; border-radius:8px;">
            <strong>MINDCARE SYSTEM</strong>
          </div>
          <div style="font-size:10pt;">&lt;-- Reports, Assignments, Responses --</div>
        </td>
        <td style="border:none; text-align:center; width:25%;">
          <div style="border:2px solid #000; padding:10px; margin:5px;">ADMIN</div>
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td colspan="3" style="border:none; text-align:center; padding-top:10px;">
          <div style="border:2px solid #000; padding:8px; width:150px; margin:0 auto;">COUNSELOR</div>
          <div style="font-size:10pt; margin-top:5px;">-- Chat, Profile --&gt; MindCare System</div>
        </td>
      </tr>
    </table>
  </div>
</div>

